Exploring data

Data from a package

So far we've covered three ways to get data into R:

  1. From flat files (either on your computer or online)
  2. From files like SAS and Excel
  3. From R objects (i.e., using load())

Many R packages come with their own data, which is very easy to load and use.

For example, the faraway package, which complements Julian Faraway's book Linear Models with R, has a dataset called worldcup. To load this dataset, run:

library(faraway)
data("worldcup")

Unlike most data objects you'll work with, datasets that are part of an R package will often have their own help files. You can access this help file using the ? operator:

?worldcup

To get a list of all of the datasets that are available in the packages you currently have loaded, run data() without an option inside the parentheses:

data()

To find out all of the datasets available within a certain package, run e.g.:

data(package = "faraway")

Plots to explore data

Exploratory data analysis is a key step in data analysis, and plotting your data in different ways is an important part of this process.

This section will focus on making useful, rather than attractive graphs, since at this stage we are focusing on exploring data for yourself rather than presenting results to others.

Here, we'll use the ggplot2 package (another member of the tidyverse!).

library(ggplot2)

The basic steps behind creating a plot with ggplot2 are:

  1. Create an object of the ggplot class, typically specifying the data and some or all of the aesthetics;
  2. Add on geoms and other elements to create and customize the plot, using +.

Initializing a ggplot object

The first step in creating a plot using ggplot2 is to create a ggplot object. It typically specifies the data frame you want to use and which aesthetics will be mapped to certain columns of that data frame.

## Generic code
object <- ggplot(data = dataframe, 
                 mapping = aes(x = column_1, y = column_2))

Plot aesthetics

Aesthetics are properties of the plot that can show certain elements of the data. For example, below, color shows (is mapped to) gender, x-position shows height, and y-position shows weight in a sample data set of measurements of children in Nepal.

Which aesthetics are required for a plot depend on which geoms you're adding to the plot. You can find out the aesthetics you can use for a geom in the "Aesthetics" section of the geom's help file. Common aesthetics include:

Code Description
x Position on x-axis
y Position on y-axis
shape Shape
color Color of border of elements
fill Color of inside of elements
size Size
alpha Transparency (1: opaque; 0: transparent)
linetype Type of line (e.g., solid, dashed)

Adding geoms

You will add one or more geoms to create the plot.
Some of the most common geoms are:

Plot type ggplot2 function
Histogram (1 numeric variable) geom_histogram
Scatterplot (2 numeric variables) geom_point
Boxplot (1 numeric variable, possibly 1 factor variable) geom_boxplot
Line graph (2 numeric variables) geom_line

Constant aesthetics

Instead of mapping an aesthetic to an element of your data, you can use a constant value for it. For example, you may want to make all the points green, rather than having color map to gender:

In this case, you'll define that aesthetic when you add the geom, outside of an aes statement.

In R, you can specify the shape of points with a number.

Examples of the shapes corresponding to different numeric choices for the shape aesthetic. For all examples, color is set to black and fill to red.

You can set a color in R using character strings for different colors.

Example of available shades of blue in R.

Useful plot additions

There are also a number of elements that you can add onto a ggplot object using +. A few that are used very frequently are:

Element Description
ggtitle Plot title
xlab, ylab x- and y-axis labels
xlim, ylim Limits of x- and y-axis

Example dataset

For the example plots, we use a dataset in the faraway package called nepali. This gives data from a study of the health of a group of Nepalese children.

library(faraway)
data(nepali)

You need to load dplyr and ggplot2:

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

Each observation is a single measurement for a child; there can be multiple observations per child. We select only the columns for child id, sex, weight, height, and age and limit the dataset to only include one measurement for each child, the child's first measurement in the dataset (by the distinct function).

nepali <- nepali %>%
  select(id, sex, wt, ht, age) %>%
  mutate(id = factor(id),
         sex = factor(sex, levels = c(1, 2),
                      labels = c("Male", "Female"))) %>%
  distinct(id, .keep_all = TRUE)

After this cleaning, the data looks like this:

head(nepali)
#>       id    sex   wt    ht age
#> 1 120011   Male 12.8  91.2  41
#> 2 120012 Female 14.9 103.9  57
#> 3 120021 Female  7.7  70.1   8
#> 4 120022 Female 12.1  86.4  35
#> 5 120023   Male 14.2  99.4  49
#> 6 120031   Male 13.9  96.4  46

Histograms

Histograms show the distribution of a single variable. Therefore, geom_histogram() requires only one main aesthetic, x. For example, to create a histogram of children's heights for the Nepali dataset (Figure @ref(fig:nepalihist1)), run:

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = ht)) + 
  geom_histogram()

Histogram of height for the first recorded measurements of each child in the nepali dataset.

If you run the code with no arguments for binwidth or bins, you will get a message saying "stat_bin() using bins = 30. You may also get a message that observations with missing values were removed.

You can add some elements to the histogram. For example (Figure @ref(fig:nepalihist2)),

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = ht)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = "lightblue", color = "black") + 
  ggtitle("Height of children") + 
  xlab("Height (cm)") + xlim(c(0, 120))

Example of adding ggplot elements to customize a histogram.

The geom geom_histogram also has special argument for setting the number of width of the bins used in the histogram. Figure @ref(fig:nepalihist3) shows an example of how you can use the bins argument .

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = ht)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = "lightblue", color = "black",
                 bins = 40)

Example of using the bins argument to change the number of bins.

Similarly, the binwidth argument can be used to set the width of bins. Figure @ref(fig:nepalihist4) shows an example with binwidths of 10 centimeters.

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = ht)) + 
  geom_histogram(fill = "lightblue", color = "black",
                 binwidth = 10)

Example of using the binwidth argument to set the width of each bin.

Scatterplots

A scatterplot shows how one variable changes as another changes. You can use the geom_point geom. For example, to create a scatterplot of height versus weight for the Nepali data (Figure @ref(fig:nepaliscatter1)), you can run:

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = ht, y = wt)) + 
  geom_point()

This scatterplot shows the relationship between children's heights and weights within the nepali dataset.

Again, you can use some of the options and additions to change the plot appearance. For example, (Figure @ref(fig:nepaliscatter2)):

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = ht, y = wt)) + 
  geom_point(color = "blue", size = 0.5) + 
  ggtitle("Weight versus Height") + 
  xlab("Height (cm)") + ylab("Weight (kg)")

Example of adding ggplot elements to customize a scatterplot.

You can also try mapping another variable in the dataset to the color aesthetic. For example, to use color to show the sex of each child (Figure @ref(fig:nepaliscatter3)), you can run:

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = ht, y = wt, color = sex)) + 
  geom_point(size = 0.5) + 
  ggtitle("Weight versus Height") + 
  xlab("Height (cm)") + ylab("Weight (kg)")

Example of mapping color to an element of the data in a scatterplot.

Barcharts

You can use the geom_bar geom to create a barchart:

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = sex)) + 
  geom_bar()

Barplot of sex for the first recorded measurements of each child in the nepali dataset. 

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = sex, fill = ht>100)) + 
  geom_bar()

Barplot of sex for the first recorded measurements of each child in the nepali dataset.

With the geom_bar geom, you can use the position argument to change how the bars for different groups are shown ("stack", "dodge", "fill"):

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = sex, fill = ht>100)) + 
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")

Barplot of sex for the first recorded measurements of each child in the nepali dataset.

Boxplots

To create a boxplot, you can use the geom_boxplot geom. For example, to create a boxplot of the heights of children in the Nepali dataset (Figure @ref(fig:nepaliboxplot1)), you can run:

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = 1, y = ht)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  xlab("")+ ylab("Height (cm)")

Boxplot of the distribution of height data for children in the nepali dataset.

You can also create separate boxplots, one for each level of a factor (Figure @ref(fig:nepaliboxplot2)).

ggplot(nepali, aes(x = sex, y = ht, group = sex)) + 
  geom_boxplot() + 
  xlab("Sex")+ ylab("Height (cm)")

Example of creating separate boxplots, divided by a categorical grouping variable in the data.

Simple statistics functions

Summary statistics

Here are some simple statistics functions:

Function Description
range() Range (minimum and maximum) of vector
min(), max() Minimum or maximum of vector
mean(), median() Mean or median of vector
sd() Standard deviation of vector
table() Number of observations per level for a factor vector
cor() Determine correlation(s) between two or more vectors
summary() Summary statistics, depends on class

All of these functions take, as the main argument, the vector or vectors for which you want the statistic. If there are missing values in the vector, you'll typically need to add an argument to say what to do with the missing values. The parameter name for many of these functions it's na.rm = TRUE or use="complete.obs".

mean(nepali$wt, na.rm = TRUE)
#> [1] 10.18432
range(nepali$ht, na.rm = TRUE)
#> [1]  52.4 104.1
sd(nepali$ht, na.rm = TRUE)
#> [1] 12.64529
table(nepali$sex)
#> 
#>   Male Female 
#>    107     93

cor(nepali$wt, nepali$ht, use = "complete.obs")
#> [1] 0.9571535
cor((nepali %>% select(wt, ht, age)), use = "complete.obs")
#>            wt        ht       age
#> wt  1.0000000 0.9571535 0.8931195
#> ht  0.9571535 1.0000000 0.9287129
#> age 0.8931195 0.9287129 1.0000000

R supports object-oriented programming (OOP). Your first taste of this shows up with the summary function. For example,

summary(nepali$wt)
#>    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
#>    3.80    7.90   10.10   10.18   12.40   16.70      15
summary(nepali$sex)
#>   Male Female 
#>    107     93

summarize function

You will often want to use these functions in conjunction with the summarize function in dplyr. For example,

nepali %>%
  summarize(mean_wt = mean(wt, na.rm = TRUE))
#>    mean_wt
#> 1 10.18432

There are also some special functions that you can use with summarize. For example, the n and the first functions:

nepali %>%
  summarize(n_children = n(), 
            first_id = first(id))
#>   n_children first_id
#> 1        200   120011

See the "summary function" section of the the RStudio Data Wrangling cheatsheet for more examples of these special functions.

Often, you will be more interested in summaries within certain groupings. You just need to group data using the group_by function (from dplyr):

nepali %>%
  group_by(sex) %>%
  summarize(mean_wt = mean(wt, na.rm = TRUE),
            n_children = n(), 
            first_id = first(id))
#> # A tibble: 2 x 4
#>      sex   mean_wt n_children first_id
#>   <fctr>     <dbl>      <int>   <fctr>
#> 1   Male 10.497980        107   120011
#> 2 Female  9.823256         93   120012

In-course exercise EDA

Exploring data from an R package with basic plots

Load the dataset called worldcup in the package faraway. Use the help file for the data to find out more about the dataset. Use some basic functions, like head, tail, colnames, str, and summary to check out the data a bit. See if you can figure out:

  • What variables are included in this dataset?
  • What class is each column currently?

  1. Create a scatterplot of the worldcup data, where each point is a player, the x-axis shows the amount of time the player played in the World Cup, and the y-axis shows the number of passes the player had. Try writing the code both with and withing "piping in" the data you want to plot into the ggplot function.
  2. Create the same scatterplot, but have each point in the scatterplot show that player's position. Add "rug plots" to the margins.
  3. Create a scatterplot of number of shots (x-axis) versus number of tackles (y-axis) for just players on one of the four teams that made the semi-finals (Spain, Netherlands, Germany, Uruguay). Use color to show player's position and shape to show player's team. For an extra challenge, also try adding each player's name on top of each point.
  4. Create a scatterplot of player time versus passes. Use color to show whether the player was on one of the top 4 teams or not.

Exploring the data using simple statistics and summarize

  1. What is the mean number of saves that players made?
  2. What is the mean number of saves just among the goalkeepers?
  3. Did players from any position other than goalkeeper make a save?
  4. How many players were there in each position?
  5. How many forwards were there on each team? Which team had the most shots in total among all its forwards?
  6. Which team(s) had the defender with the most tackles?

If you have extra time, continuing using the "Data Wrangling" cheatsheet to come up with some other ideas for how you can explore this data, and write up and test code to do that.
